Game.Name: Sightwaves
Game.Description:
This was our submission for Global Game Jam 2017, the first game jam that we participated in. It was developed by John Wolfson, Will Dixon and Daniel Dennis at the University of Lincoln.
The theme of this jam was Waves. With this we came up with the idea of the player not being able to see through traditional means but, instead seeing the world through sound. So as a player, you need to make noise in order to perceive the world around you. Find your way through abandoned structures and solve puzzles in order to find your way back home.

Game.Name: The Lone Astronaut
Game.Description:
This was out submission for Global Game Jam 2018. It was developed by John Wolfson, Will Dixon, Daniel Dennis, Tim Weightman and Luke Garside at the University of Lincoln.
The theme for this jam was Transmission. With this in mind and inspiration from 'The Martian', we came up with the idea of the player being trapped on the planet Mars and needing to complete many different puzzles and problems in order to escape back home to Earth.

Game.Name: Time To Kill
Game.Description:
This was our submission for CanJam 2017. It was developed by John Wolfson, Will Dixon, Daniel Dennis, Tim Weightman and Luke Garside at the University of Lincoln.
The theme for this jam was Time. With this we came up with the concept of time speeding up or slowing down based on the players ability. Shoot your way past your enemies to get to the bomb at the end of each stage to disarm it before it blows you all to kingdom come.

Game.Name: Revenge of Johny 5
Game.Description:
This was our submission for CanJam 2018. It was developed by John Wolfson, Will Dixon, Tim Weightman and Luke Garside at the University of Lincoln.
The theme for this jam was Surprisingly Spooky. Navigate an abandoned labratory be wary not to be caught by the ruthless murdering robot patrolling its corridors. Collect the three different parts of the EMP before escaping to put an end to his rampage and uncover the mystery of what happened to the staff along the way.

Game.Name: Home Is Where The Mech Is
Game.Description:
this was our submission for Global Game Jam with the addition of an offline mode. It was developed by John Wolfson, Will DIxon, Daniel Dennis and Tim Weightman at the University of Lincoln.
Suit up in your mech to defend your home from the evil corporations tanks and drones seeking to destroy it! Originally developed with Twitch integration, this has unfortunetely broken due to changes in Twitch's API though the offline mode still functions as it should.

Game.Name: Lunarstein
Game.Description:
This was our submission for CanJam 2019. It was developed by John Wolfson, Will Dixon, Daniel Dennis and Tim Weightman at the University of Lincoln.
The theme for this jam was Legacy. The evil Computer Science Society has started to use technology for evil! Only the Game Development Society stands between them and total domination! Progress your way through their spaceship, destroying their generators to bring it down before making your escape!

Game.Name: PURRRPETRATOR
Game.Description:
This was our submission for Spook Jam 2019. It was developed by John Wolfson, Will Dixon, Daniel Dennis and Tim Weightman at the University of Lincoln.
The theme for this jam was Hidden Below. Play as a playful ginger cat who is stuck inside an Egyptian crypt. Do your best as a cat and knock over as many Egyptian pots as possible before Anubis gets tired of your destructive behavior and pulls you back! This is also playable on mouse and keyboard though is better on controller.

Game.Name: Repair-a-bots
Game.Description:
This was out submission to Global Game Jam 2020. it was developed by John Wolfson, Will Dixon, Daniel Dennis and Tim Weightman at the University of Lincoln.
The theme for this jam was Repair. Help out your bigger bot friend so that he can destroy the evil robot monsters around the world. Your three small friends will need to aid you by picking up scrap to heal, boost and strengthen you. For 1-4 players.

Game.Name: Lost Castle
Game.Description:
This was our submission for Global Game Jam 2021. It was developed by John Wolfson, Will Dixon and Daniel Dennis remotely during COVID lockdown as part of the Midlands Jam Site.
The theme for this year was Lost & Found. Your castle has been taken from you! Sneak back in to take back your gold, sword and free your friends! Don't let the guards see you as once the alarm is raised, many more will coming hunting for your head!

Game.Name: Meiyo Doggo
Game.Description:
This was out submission for Global Game Jam 2022. It was developed by John Wolfson, Will Dixon and Daniel Dennis at the University of Lincoln.
The theme for this jam was Duality. You were once a strong and skilled samurai though after many adventures you sought retirement. This was not to be though after a barbaric attack on your childhood village resulting in the hunt of a lifetime for man's best friend. This is also playable with mouse and keyboard though it is better on controller.
